@flexiarg structure/block-as-futonic-revolution
@title A Block Is One Revolution of the Futonic Loop
@sigils [🥁/節]
@keywords block, futonic-loop, revolution, commit, articulation, bar, measure, hinge, lifecycle
@audience mission operators, agents, anyone reasoning about the unit of attestable work
@tone analytic-foundational
@factor Concentration (samādhi) — a single revolution held coherently
@style pattern
@references [futon-theory/futonic-logic futon-theory/proof-path structure/cook-ting structure/hinge-point structure/mana-allostasis invariant-coherence/drain-channel-shape]

! conclusion:
  A block is one full revolution of the futonic loop:
  象 (input) → 部 (choose decomposition regime) → 咅 (articulate) →
  鹽 (compose; ⿱ 鹵 皿) → 香 (sense) + 🔮 (regulate) →
  未知 (act-within transitional state) → 味 (evaluate). The git
  commit is the 咅 → 鹽 step — articulation composing latent work
  (鹵) into durable substrate (皿) as a stable whole. Block boundaries
  are recognised at hinges (structure/cook-ting), not scheduled. The
  block is the smallest unit the operator can attest to and the
  system can record durably.

  + context:
    Multiple framings converge on the same structural unit:
      - Bitcoin: a block is the miner-attested transaction set.
      - Clojure STM: a `dosync` body is one transaction.
      - Music: a bar (小節 / 節) is a unit of metrical structure —
        the music does not pause at bar lines, but the bar gives a
        framework for phrasing.
      - Futonic methodology: PSR → apply → PUR is one block-shaped
        revolution.
    All four frame the same shape: a coherent, attestable unit of
    transition between two stable states. Naming this convergence
    "block" lets the operator and the system reason about the same
    thing.

  + IF:
    The operator has been editing a working tree (or composing a
    mission section, or running a session, or otherwise doing
    futonic work), and a hinge appears.

  + HOWEVER:
    A block does not close at a fixed schedule, and not every commit
    is a complete block. A block-closure is complete only if all
    five phases have run:

      1. **Identification** — the operator perceives the hinge.
         Cleavage in the work has become visible. (`structure/cook-ting`)
      2. **Specification** — the included changes are nameable. The
         operator can say "this block contains X." Without
         specification, the commit message is vague.
      3. **Elaboration** — the structure is articulated (commit
         message; optionally a wiring diagram, paired test, lab
         note). The block has a *shape* in addition to its content.
      4. **Passion** — the work has been *done*. Embodied effort has
         been discharged. (Not a free closure; mana-allostasis
         requires the passion phase to award real, not counterfeit,
         mana.)
      5. **Closure** — 鹽 forms: 鹵 (the latent work) and 皿 (the
         durable substrate) compose into a stable whole. The git
         commit lands.

    Skipping any phase produces a forced cut, dulling the blade
    (cook-ting). All five phases must be present for the revolution
    to count as one block.

  + THEN:
    Treat the block as the unit the system records. Pressure
    dissipates at block-closure, not at file-level commits. The
    operator's task is to perceive when a block is approaching
    completion through the five phases — not to manage individual
    file changes.

  + BECAUSE:
    Without a coherent unit, every dirty file is its own anxiety.
    With blocks, the operator's attention is on whether the *current*
    block is approaching closure — a single coherent question rather
    than N file-level questions. The futonic loop already names the
    structure; "block" is the operational name for one of its
    revolutions.

  + APPLICATION-TO-WORKING-TREE:
    A working-tree block is the set of file changes the operator
    includes in `git commit -m "..."`. The commit message IS the
    block header. A block may produce 1+N commits if the operator
    splits its scope for clarity (e.g., the futon3c sweep on
    2026-05-03 produced 9 commits inside what was conceptually one
    "clear all WIP" block); the block-id (in commit footer or git
    notes) binds the commits.

  + APPLICATION-TO-MISSIONS:
    A mission-phase transition (IDENTIFY → MAP, MAP → DERIVE, etc.)
    is a block closure. The phase output (the new section in the
    mission doc) is the 鹽 of that revolution. Mission docs across
    the stack already follow this rhythm; naming it "block-shaped"
    lets the invariant family reason about it uniformly.

  + APPLICATION-TO-AGENT-EVIDENCE:
    Each agent chat turn is automatically one block — evidence-per-
    turn is the *automatic* form of block-discipline. The unit is
    the same as a working-tree block; the recording cadence differs
    (turn-based vs hinge-based). This makes block-discipline
    symmetric across agent and operator activity.

  + DIAGNOSTIC:
    - Commits are large and infrequent: hinges have been missed.
      Pressure rises; eventually a stop-the-line forces an awkward
      multi-block close. The "504 file commit" pattern.
    - Commits are tiny and constant: the operator is over-committing
      at non-hinges. Each commit is a half-formed 鹽; cumulative
      attention cost rises (mana drains via the *committing-itself*
      channel).
    - Commit messages are vague ("WIP", "fixes", "stuff"): 咅
      (articulation) didn't form cleanly. The block isn't really
      one block — it's an in-flight transaction the operator hasn't
      finished perceiving.
    - The operator's hand is hovering over `git commit`: blade in
      wrong place. Step back. Look for the cleavage. Do not force.
      (cook-ting)

  + ANTI-PATTERNS:
    - **jj-style auto-commit**: every working-tree state is a
      change-id. Defeats the operator-attestation that defines a
      block. The operator's commit message — the 咅 — is what makes
      a block one block.
    - **"Commit early, commit often" as a rule**: a discipline-style
      injunction that forces cuts at non-hinges. Dulls the blade
      when applied uniformly; useful only when phrased as
      "perceive hinges actively, do not let blocks grow indefinite."
    - **One-commit-per-file**: each commit becomes a half-block;
      metrical structure breaks. The bar disappears.
    - **Closure without passion**: closing a block without the
      work-phase (rubber-stamp commits, automated formatters as
      "blocks", squash-merges of unfinished branches). Awards
      counterfeit mana; produces hollow consonance.

  + COMPOSITION-WITH-SIBLINGS:
    Blocks compose with PSR/PUR cycles, mission-phase blocks,
    session-blocks, day-blocks, excursion-blocks. A single revolution
    of the futonic loop may be wholly contained within (e.g.) a
    session-block, or may span multiple session-blocks if the work
    is genuinely large. The block-id (when assigned) is the binding
    that holds the revolution coherent across its containers.

  + REFERENCES:
    - futon-theory/futonic-logic — formal definition of 象/部/咅/鹽/香/🔮/未知/味.
    - futon-theory/proof-path — the 8-phase auditable event chain that a block manifests at the substrate layer.
    - structure/cook-ting — hinge-recognition; perceive cleavages, do not force.
    - structure/hinge-point — the structural slot where a block can close.
    - structure/mana-allostasis — the dynamic the block sits inside (each block-close is a mana award).
    - invariant-coherence/drain-channel-shape — how the new working-tree drain channel and existing bounded-disposition siblings cohere under one faculty.
